!>  \brief
!>  This module contains the procedures for multiplication of a square triangular matrix in various transpositions with a general matrix.<br>
!>
!>  \details
!>  Such matrix multiplications frequently occur in solving general or triangular systems of equations with single or multiple right-hand sides (as a matrix).<br>
!>  Each system of linear equation is comprised of
!>  <ol>
!>      <li>    a coefficient matrix \f$A\f$, which is assumed to be [triangular](@ref pm_matrixClass::triang_type) in this module.<br>
!>      <li>    the matrix of unknowns \f$X\f$ for which the system must be solved,
!>      <li>    the intercept matrix \f$B\f$ on the right-hand-side of the system of equations,
!>              which will be overwritten by the solution within this module.<br>
!>  </ol>
!>
!>  \note
!>  For general matrix-matrix or matrix-vector multiplications, see [pm_matrixMulAdd](@ref pm_matrixMulAdd).<br>
!>
!>  The procedures under the generic interface [setMatMulTri](@ref pm_matrixMulTri::setMatMulTri)
!>  return the solution of the following corresponding **linear triangular system of equations**,
!>
!>   **System of Equations**                                                |   **Solution (corresponding matrix multiplication)**                  |   BLAS routines
!>   -----------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------|--------------------------------
!>   \f$\ms{C}^{-1}             \ms{X}^{\hphantom{-T}}  = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{C}^\hphantom{T}    \ms{I}      \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trmv}~/~\ms{?trmm}\f$
!>   \f$\ms{C}^{-T}             \ms{X}^{\hphantom{-T}}  = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{C}^{T}             \ms{I}      \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trmv}~/~\ms{?trmm}\f$
!>   \f$\ms{C}^{-H}             \ms{X}^{\hphantom{-T}}  = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{C}^{H}             \ms{I}      \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trmv}~/~\ms{?trmm}\f$
!>   \f$\ms{X}^{\hphantom{-T}}  \ms{C}^{-1}             = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{I}^{\hphantom{T}}  \ms{C}      \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trmv}~/~\ms{?trmm}\f$
!>   \f$\ms{X}^{\hphantom{-T}}  \ms{C}^{-T}             = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{I}^{\hphantom{T}}  \ms{C}^{T}  \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trmv}~/~\ms{?trmm}\f$
!>   \f$\ms{X}^{\hphantom{-T}}  \ms{C}^{-H}             = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{I}^{\hphantom{T}}  \ms{C}^{H}  \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trmv}~/~\ms{?trmm}\f$
!>
!>   **System of Equations**                                                |   **Solution (corresponding matrix multiplication)**                  |   BLAS routines
!>   -----------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------|--------------------------------
!>   \f$\ms{C}^{\hphantom{T}}   \ms{X}^{\hphantom{T}}   = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{C}^{-1}            \ms{I}      \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trsv}~/~\ms{?trsm}\f$
!>   \f$\ms{C}^T                \ms{X}^{\hphantom{T}}   = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{C}^{-T}            \ms{I}      \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trsv}~/~\ms{?trsm}\f$
!>   \f$\ms{C}^H                \ms{X}^{\hphantom{T}}   = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{C}^{-H}            \ms{I}      \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trsv}~/~\ms{?trsm}\f$
!>   \f$\ms{X}^{\hphantom{T}}   \ms{C}^{\hphantom{T}}   = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{I}^{\hphantom{-T}} \ms{C}^{-1} \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trsv}~/~\ms{?trsm}\f$
!>   \f$\ms{X}^{\hphantom{T}}   \ms{C}^T                = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{I}^{\hphantom{-T}} \ms{C}^{-T} \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trsv}~/~\ms{?trsm}\f$
!>   \f$\ms{X}^{\hphantom{T}}   \ms{C}^H                = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{I}^{\hphantom{-T}} \ms{C}^{-H} \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trsv}~/~\ms{?trsm}\f$
!>
!>  where
!>  <ol>
!>      <li>    \f$\cdot^-\f$ represents a matrix inversion.
!>      <li>    \f$\cdot^T\f$ represents a Symmetric transpose.
!>      <li>    \f$\cdot^H\f$ represents a Hermitian transpose.
!>      <li>    \f$\ms{I}\f$ represents the **Right-Hand-Side (RHS)** of the system of linear equations.
!>      <li>    \f$\ms{C}\f$ represents the **triangular matrix** of coefficients of the system of linear equations.
!>      <li>    \f$\ms{X}\f$ represents the **unknown matrix** for which the system of linear equations must be solved (or equivalently, the result of the corresponding matrix multiplication).
!>  </ol>
!>  Computational efficiency and practical considerations require the (matrix multiplication) solution to be
!>  written to \f$\ms{I}\f$ instead of being returned explicitly to a separate argument as \f$\ms{X}\f$.<br>
!>
!>  \lapack{3.11}
!>  `STRMV`, `DTRMV`, `CTRMV`, and `ZTRMV`,
!>  `STRSV`, `DTRSV`, `CTRSV`, and `ZTRSV`,
!>  `STRMM`, `DTRMM`, `CTRMM`, and `ZTRMM`,
!>  `STRSM`, `DTRSM`, `CTRSM`, and `ZTRSM`.<br>
!>
!>  \see
!>  [nothing](@ref pm_array::nothing)<br>
!>  [inversion](@ref pm_matrixInv::inversion)<br>
!>  [lowerDiag](@ref pm_matrixClass::lowerDiag)<br>
!>  [upperDiag](@ref pm_matrixClass::upperDiag)<br>
!>  [lowerUnit](@ref pm_matrixClass::lowerUnit)<br>
!>  [upperUnit](@ref pm_matrixClass::upperUnit)<br>
!>  [transSymm](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transSymm)<br>
!>  [transHerm](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transHerm)<br>
!>  [transOrth](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transOrth)<br>
!>  [transUnit](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transUnit)<br>
!>  [setMatMulAdd](@ref pm_matrixMulAdd::setMatMulAdd)<br>
!>
!>  \todo
!>  \phigh
!>  The BLAS routines `?TPMV`, `?TPSV`, `?TBMV` and `?TBSV` for Linear Full and Band packing format of the triangular input matrix must be implemented.<br>
!>
!>  \todo
!>  \pmed
!>  A benchmark comparison of the procedures of [setMatMulTri](@ref pm_matrixMulTri::setMatMulTri) with the optimized BLAS routine calls would be informative.<br>
!>
!>  \test
!>  [test_pm_matrixMul](@ref test_pm_matrixMul)<br>
!>
!>  \final
!>
!>  \author
!>  \AmirShahmoradi, Friday 1:54 AM, April 21, 2017, Institute for Computational Engineering and Sciences (ICES), The University of Texas, Austin, TX

!%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

module pm_matrixMulTri

    use pm_kind, only: SK, IK, LK
    use pm_matrixClass, only: lowerDiag, lowerDiag_type
    use pm_matrixClass, only: upperDiag, upperDiag_type
    use pm_matrixClass, only: lowerUnit, lowerUnit_type
    use pm_matrixClass, only: upperUnit, upperUnit_type
    use pm_matrixTrans, only: transSymm, transSymm_type
    use pm_matrixTrans, only: transHerm, transHerm_type
    use pm_matrixTrans, only: transOrth, transOrth_type
    use pm_matrixTrans, only: transUnit, transUnit_type
    use pm_matrixInv, only: inversion, inversion_type
    use pm_array, only: nothing, nothing_type

    implicit none

    character(*, SK), parameter :: MODULE_NAME = "@pm_matrixMulTri"

!%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

    !>  \brief
    !>  Return the matrix solution to the system of linear equations with a triangular coefficient matrix \f$\ms{C}\f$.
    !>
    !>  \details
    !>  The procedures under the generic interface [setMatMulTri](@ref pm_matrixMulTri::setMatMulTri)
    !>  return the solution of the following corresponding **linear triangular system of equations**,
    !>
    !>   **System of Equations**                                                |   **Solution (corresponding matrix multiplication)**                  |   BLAS routines
    !>   -----------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------|--------------------------------
    !>   \f$\ms{C}^{-1}             \ms{X}^{\hphantom{-T}}  = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{C}^\hphantom{T}    \ms{I}      \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trmv}~/~\ms{?trmm}\f$
    !>   \f$\ms{C}^{-T}             \ms{X}^{\hphantom{-T}}  = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{C}^{T}             \ms{I}      \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trmv}~/~\ms{?trmm}\f$
    !>   \f$\ms{C}^{-H}             \ms{X}^{\hphantom{-T}}  = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{C}^{H}             \ms{I}      \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trmv}~/~\ms{?trmm}\f$
    !>   \f$\ms{X}^{\hphantom{-T}}  \ms{C}^{-1}             = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{I}^{\hphantom{T}}  \ms{C}      \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trmv}~/~\ms{?trmm}\f$
    !>   \f$\ms{X}^{\hphantom{-T}}  \ms{C}^{-T}             = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{I}^{\hphantom{T}}  \ms{C}^{T}  \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trmv}~/~\ms{?trmm}\f$
    !>   \f$\ms{X}^{\hphantom{-T}}  \ms{C}^{-H}             = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{I}^{\hphantom{T}}  \ms{C}^{H}  \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trmv}~/~\ms{?trmm}\f$
    !>
    !>   **System of Equations**                                                |   **Solution (corresponding matrix multiplication)**                  |   BLAS routines
    !>   -----------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------|--------------------------------
    !>   \f$\ms{C}^{\hphantom{T}}   \ms{X}^{\hphantom{T}}   = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{C}^{-1}            \ms{I}      \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trsv}~/~\ms{?trsm}\f$
    !>   \f$\ms{C}^T                \ms{X}^{\hphantom{T}}   = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{C}^{-T}            \ms{I}      \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trsv}~/~\ms{?trsm}\f$
    !>   \f$\ms{C}^H                \ms{X}^{\hphantom{T}}   = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{C}^{-H}            \ms{I}      \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trsv}~/~\ms{?trsm}\f$
    !>   \f$\ms{X}^{\hphantom{T}}   \ms{C}^{\hphantom{T}}   = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{I}^{\hphantom{-T}} \ms{C}^{-1} \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trsv}~/~\ms{?trsm}\f$
    !>   \f$\ms{X}^{\hphantom{T}}   \ms{C}^T                = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{I}^{\hphantom{-T}} \ms{C}^{-T} \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trsv}~/~\ms{?trsm}\f$
    !>   \f$\ms{X}^{\hphantom{T}}   \ms{C}^H                = \alpha\ms{I}\f$   |   \f$ \ms{I} \leftarrow \alpha \ms{I}^{\hphantom{-T}} \ms{C}^{-H} \f$ |   \f$\ms{?trsv}~/~\ms{?trsm}\f$
    !>
    !>  where
    !>  <ol>
    !>      <li>    \f$\cdot^-\f$ represents a matrix inversion.
    !>      <li>    \f$\cdot^T\f$ represents a Symmetric transpose.
    !>      <li>    \f$\cdot^H\f$ represents a Hermitian transpose.
    !>      <li>    \f$\ms{I}\f$ represents the **Right-Hand-Side (RHS)** (i.e., the intercept) of the system of linear equations.
    !>      <li>    \f$\ms{C}\f$ represents the **triangular matrix** of coefficients of the system of linear equations.
    !>      <li>    \f$\ms{X}\f$ represents the **unknown matrix** for which the system of linear equations must be solved (or equivalently, the result of the corresponding matrix multiplication).
    !>  </ol>
    !>  Computational efficiency and practical considerations require the (matrix multiplication) solution to be
    !>  written to \f$\ms{I}\f$ instead of being returned explicitly to a separate argument as \f$\ms{X}\f$.<br>
    !>
    !>  \note
    !>  For general matrix-matrix or matrix-vector multiplications, see [pm_matrixMulAdd](@ref pm_matrixMulAdd).<br>
    !>
    !>  <b>Multiplication scheme of this generic interface</b><br>
    !>
    !>   \f$\ms{matA}\f$ shape and class                    |   \f$\ms{matB}\f$ shape and class             |   **Solution (corresponding output matrix multiplication)**
    !>   ---------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    !>   \f$\ms{nrow} \times \ms{nrow}\f$ triangular        |   \f$\ms{nrow}\f$ column vector               |   \f$\ms{matB}(1:\ms{nrow})               \leftarrow                  \ms{operationA}\left(\ms{matA}(1:\ms{ncol}, 1:\ms{ncol})\right) \times \ms{matB}(1:\ms{nrow})\f$
    !>   \f$\ms{nrow} \times \ms{nrow}\f$ triangular        |   \f$\ms{nrow} \times \ms{ncol}\f$ general    |   \f$\ms{matB}(1:\ms{nrow}, 1:\ms{ncol})  \leftarrow \alpha \times    \ms{operationA}\left(\ms{matA}(1:\ms{ncol}, 1:\ms{ncol})\right) \times \ms{matB}(1:\ms{nrow}, 1:\ms{ncol})\f$
    !>   \f$\ms{nrow} \times \ms{ncol}\f$ general           |   \f$\ms{ncol} \times \ms{ncol}\f$ triangular |   \f$\ms{matA}(1:\ms{nrow}, 1:\ms{ncol})  \leftarrow \alpha \times    \ms{matA}(1:\ms{nrow}, 1:\ms{ncol}) \times \ms{operationB}\left(\ms{matB}(1:\ms{ncol}, 1:\ms{ncol})\right)\f$
    !>
    !>  \param[inout]   matA        :   The input/output `contiguous` matrix of shape `(:,:)` of,
    !>                                  <ol>
    !>                                      <li>    type `complex` of kind \CKALL, or
    !>                                      <li>    type `real` of kind \RKALL,
    !>                                  </ol>
    !>                                  It can be,
    !>                                  <ol>
    !>                                      <li>    an upper/lower subset of a triangular square matrix \f$\ms{C}\f$ (i.e., the coefficient matrix in the system of linear equations).<br>
    !>                                              In such a case, `matA` is read-only with `intent(in)`.<br>
    !>                                      <li>    a general matrix in the multiplication (corresponding to the **intercept matrix** in the right-hand-side of the system of linear equations).<br>
    !>                                              In such a case, `matA` has `intent(inout)` and its contents will be overwritten by the solution on return.<br>
    !>                                  </ol>
    !>  \param[in]      classA      :   The input scalar that can be either,
    !>                                  <ol>
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [upperDiag](@ref pm_matrixClass::upperDiag) for `matA` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that `matA` is an upper-diagonal triangular matrix.<br>
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [lowerDiag](@ref pm_matrixClass::lowerDiag) for `matA` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that `matA` is an lower-diagonal triangular matrix.<br>
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [upperUnit](@ref pm_matrixClass::upperUnit) for `matA` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that `matA` is an upper-unit triangular matrix.<br>
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [lowerUnit](@ref pm_matrixClass::lowerUnit) for `matA` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that `matA` is an lower-unit triangular matrix.<br>
    !>                                  </ol>
    !>                                  This argument is merely a convenience to resolve the different procedure functionalities within this generic interface.<br>
    !>                                  (**optional**, default = [general matrix](@ref pm_matrixClass::genrecmat_type). It must be present **if and only if** the input argument `operationA` is also present and `classB` is missing.)
    !>  \param[in]      operationA  :   The input scalar that can be either,
    !>                                  <ol>
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [nothing](@ref pm_array::nothing) for `matA` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that a [Symmetric transpose](@ref pm_matrixTrans) of `matA` should be used in the matrix-matrix or matrix-vector multiplication.
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [transSymm](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transSymm) for `matA` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that a [Symmetric transpose](@ref pm_matrixTrans) of `matA` should be used in the matrix-matrix or matrix-vector multiplication.
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [transHerm](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transHerm) for `matA` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that a [Hermitian transpose](@ref pm_matrixTrans) of the specified subset of `matA` should be used in the matrix-matrix or matrix-vector multiplication.
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [inversion](@ref pm_matrixInv::inversion) for `matA` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that the inverse of `matA` should be used in the matrix-matrix or matrix-vector multiplication.
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [transOrth](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transOrth) for `matA` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that an [Orthogonal transpose](@ref pm_matrixTrans) of `matA` should be used in the matrix-matrix or matrix-vector multiplication.
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [transUnit](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transUnit) for `matA` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that an [Unitary transpose](@ref pm_matrixTrans) of `matA` should be used in the matrix-matrix or matrix-vector multiplication.
    !>                                  </ol>
    !>                                  This argument is merely a convenience to resolve the different procedure functionalities within this generic interface.<br>
    !>                                  (**optional**. It must be present **if and only if** `classA` is also present. If missing, the specified `matA` will be used as is, without any operations performed on it.)
    !>  \param[inout]   matB        :   The input/output `contiguous` matrix of shape `(:,:)` of the same type and kind as `matA`,
    !>                                  containing the subset of the intercept matrix \f$\ms{I}\f$ in the system of linear equations.<br>
    !>                                  It can be,
    !>                                  <ol>
    !>                                      <li>    an upper/lower subset of a triangular square matrix \f$\ms{C}\f$ (i.e., the coefficient matrix in the system of linear equations).<br>
    !>                                              In such a case, `matB` is read-only with `intent(in)`.<br>
    !>                                      <li>    a general matrix in the multiplication (corresponding to the **intercept matrix** in the right-hand-side of the system of linear equations).<br>
    !>                                              In such a case, `matB` has `intent(inout)` and its contents will be overwritten by the solution on return.<br>
    !>                                  </ol>
    !>  \param[in]      classB      :   The input scalar that can be either,
    !>                                  <ol>
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [upperDiag](@ref pm_matrixClass::upperDiag) for `matB` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that `matB` is an upper-diagonal triangular matrix.<br>
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [lowerDiag](@ref pm_matrixClass::lowerDiag) for `matB` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that `matB` is an lower-diagonal triangular matrix.<br>
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [upperUnit](@ref pm_matrixClass::upperUnit) for `matB` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that `matB` is an upper-unit triangular matrix.<br>
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [lowerUnit](@ref pm_matrixClass::lowerUnit) for `matB` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that `matB` is an lower-unit triangular matrix.<br>
    !>                                  </ol>
    !>                                  This argument is merely a convenience to resolve the different procedure functionalities within this generic interface.<br>
    !>                                  (**optional**, default = [general matrix](@ref pm_matrixClass::genrecmat_type). It must be present **if and only if** the input argument `operationB` is also present, `matB` is of rank `2`, and `classA` is missing.)
    !>  \param[in]      operationB  :   The input scalar that can be either,
    !>                                  <ol>
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [transSymm](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transSymm) for `matB` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that a [Symmetric transpose](@ref pm_matrixTrans) of `matB` should be used in the matrix-matrix or matrix-vector multiplication.
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [transHerm](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transHerm) for `matB` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that a [Hermitian transpose](@ref pm_matrixTrans) of the specified subset of `matB` should be used in the matrix-matrix or matrix-vector multiplication.
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [inversion](@ref pm_matrixInv::inversion) for `matB` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that the inverse of `matB` should be used in the matrix-matrix or matrix-vector multiplication.
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [transOrth](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transOrth) for `matB` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that an [Orthogonal transpose](@ref pm_matrixTrans) of `matB` should be used in the matrix-matrix or matrix-vector multiplication.
    !>                                      <li>    the constant [transUnit](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transUnit) for `matB` of any type of any kind,
    !>                                              implying that an [Unitary transpose](@ref pm_matrixTrans) of `matB` should be used in the matrix-matrix or matrix-vector multiplication.
    !>                                  </ol>
    !>                                  This argument is merely a convenience to resolve the different procedure functionalities within this generic interface.<br>
    !>                                  (**optional**. It must be present **if and only if** `classB` is also present. If missing, the specified `matB` will be used as is, without any operations performed on it.)
    !>  \param[in]      alpha       :   The input scalar of the same type and kind as `matA`, containing the coefficient \f$\alpha\f$ with which the resulting matrix multiplication will be multiplied.<br>
    !>                                  (**optional**, default = `1`. It must be present if both `nrow` and `ncol` are also present.)
    !>  \param[in]      nrow        :   The input non-negative scalar of type `integer` of default kind \IK, containing the number of rows of the output general matrix (either `matA` or `matB`) in the multiplication.<br>
    !>                                  (**optional**, default = `size(matA, 1)` or `size(matB, 1)`, whichever is the general (non-triangular) matrix in the multiplication. It must be present if any of the following arguments are also present.)
    !>  \param[in]      ncol        :   The input non-negative scalar of type `integer` of default kind \IK,
    !>                                  containing the number of columns of the general matrix (either `matA` or `matB`) in the multiplication:
    !>                                  <ol>
    !>                                      <li>    If `matA` is the general matrix then the subset `matA(roffA + 1 : roffA + nrow, coffA + 1 : coffA + ncol)` will be used in the multiplication.<br>
    !>                                      <li>    If `matB` is the general matrix then the subset `matB(roffB + 1 : roffB + nrow, coffB + 1 : coffB + ncol)` will be used in the multiplication.<br>
    !>                                  </ol>
    !>                                  (**optional**, default = `size(matA, 2)` or `size(matB, 2)`, whichever is the general matrix in the multiplication. It must not be present if the general matrix is a column vector.)
    !>  \param[in]      incB        :   The input non-zero scalar `integer` of default kind \IK, containing the stride of the input argument `matB(:)`.<br>
    !>                                  <ol>
    !>                                      <li>    A positive value implies the multiplication to be performed on the subset `matB(1 : 1 + (nrow - 1) * incB : incB)`.
    !>                                      <li>    A negative value implies the multiplication to be performed on the subset `matB(1 + (1 - nrow) * incB : 1 : incB)`.
    !>                                  </ol>
    !>                                  (**optional**, default = `1`. It can be present only if `matB` is a column vector of shape `(:)`.)
    !>  \param[in]      roffA       :   The input non-negative scalar of type `integer` of default kind \IK containing the <b>off</b>set from the first <b>r</b>ow of the input matrix `matA`,
    !>                                  such that `matA(1 + roffA, 1 + coffA)` marks the top-left corner of the block of `matA` used in the multiplication.<br>
    !>                                  (**optional**, default = `0`. It must be present if `ncol` is present.)
    !>  \param[in]      coffA       :   The input non-negative scalar of type `integer` of default kind \IK containing the <b>off</b>set from the first <b>c</b>olumn of the input matrix `matA`,
    !>                                  such that `matA(1 + roffA, 1 + coffA)` marks the top-left corner of the block of `matA` used in the multiplication.<br>
    !>                                  (**optional**, default = `0`. It must be present if `ncol` is present.)
    !>  \param[in]      roffB       :   The input non-negative scalar of type `integer` of default kind \IK containing the <b>off</b>set from the first <b>r</b>ow of the input matrix `matB`,
    !>                                  such that `matB(1 + roffB, 1 + coffB)` marks the top-left corner of the block of `matB` used in the multiplication.<br>
    !>                                  (**optional**, default = `0`. It must be present if `ncol` is present.)
    !>  \param[in]      coffB       :   The input non-negative scalar of type `integer` of default kind \IK containing the <b>off</b>set from the first <b>c</b>olumn of the input matrix `matB`,
    !>                                  such that `matB(1 + roffB, 1 + coffB)` marks the top-left corner of the block of `matB` used in the multiplication.<br>
    !>                                  (**optional**, default = `0`. It must be present if `ncol` is present.)
    !>
    !>  \interface{setMatMulTri}
    !>  \code{.F90}
    !>
    !>      use pm_matrixMulTri, only: inversion, nothing
    !>      use pm_matrixMulTri, only: upperDiag, lowerDiag
    !>      use pm_matrixMulTri, only: upperUnit, lowerUnit
    !>      use pm_matrixMulTri, only: transSymm, transHerm
    !>      use pm_matrixMulTri, only: transOrth, transUnit
    !>      use pm_matrixMulTri, only: setMatMulTri
    !>
    !>      ! BLAS - LEVEL 2: ?TRMV / ?TRSV - SIMPLIFIED INTERFACE.
    !>
    !>      call setMatMulTri(matA(:,:), classA, operationA, matB(:))
    !>
    !>      ! BLAS - LEVEL 2: ?TRMV / ?TRSV - contiguous interface.
    !>
    !>      call setMatMulTri(matA(:,:), classA, operationA, matB(:), nrow, roffA, coffA, incB)
    !>
    !>      ! BLAS - LEVEL 3: ?TRMM / ?TRSM - SIMPLIFIED INTERFACE.
    !>
    !>      call setMatMulTri(matA(:,:), classA, operationA, matB(:,:), alpha = alpha)
    !>      call setMatMulTri(matA(:,:), matB(:,:), classB, operationB, alpha = alpha)
    !>
    !>      ! BLAS - LEVEL 3: ?TRMM / ?TRSM - contiguous interface.
    !>
    !>      call setMatMulTri(matA(:,:), classA, operationA, matB(:,:), alpha, nrow, ncol, roffA, coffA, roffB, coffB)
    !>      call setMatMulTri(matA(:,:), matB(:,:), classB, operationB, alpha, nrow, ncol, roffA, coffA, roffB, coffB)
    !>
    !>  \endcode
    !>
    !>  \warning
    !>  The input triangular matrix must be square.<br>
    !>  The condition `all(0 <= [nrow, ncol])` must hold for the corresponding input arguments.<br>
    !>  The condition `all(0 <= [roffA, coffA])` must hold for the corresponding input arguments.<br>
    !>  The condition `all(0 <= [roffB, coffB])` must hold for the corresponding input arguments.<br>
    !>  The condition `all(0 <= [roffB, coffB])` must hold for the corresponding input arguments.<br>
    !>  The shapes of the input matrices must be consistent with each other for the target multiplication setup.<br>
    !>  \vericons
    !>
    !>  \warnpure
    !>
    !>  \lapack{3.11}
    !>  `STRMV`, `DTRMV`, `CTRMV`, and `ZTRMV`,
    !>  `STRSV`, `DTRSV`, `CTRSV`, and `ZTRSV`,
    !>  `STRMM`, `DTRMM`, `CTRMM`, and `ZTRMM`,
    !>  `STRSM`, `DTRSM`, `CTRSM`, and `ZTRSM`.<br>
    !>
    !>  \cond excluded
    !>  \lapackint{setMatMulTri}
    !>
    !>  \todo The following table must be corrected.
    !>  BLAS/LAPACK interface arguments |   [setMatMulTri](@ref pm_matrixMulTri::setMatMulTri) interface arguments
    !>  --------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    !>  `operationA = "N"`              |   `operationA` argument is missing.
    !>  `operationA = "T"`              |   `operationA =` [transSymm](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transSymm)
    !>  `operationB = "C"`              |   `operationA =` [transHerm](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transHerm)
    !>  `operationB = "N"`              |   `operationB` argument is missing.
    !>  `operationB = "T"`              |   `operationB =` [transSymmB](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transSymmB)
    !>  `operationB = "C"`              |   `operationB =` [transHermB](@ref pm_matrixTrans::transHermB)
    !>  `m`                             |   `nrow`
    !>  `n`                             |   `ncol`
    !>  `k`                             |   `ndum`
    !>  `alpha`                         |   `alpha`
    !>  `a = A(i,j)`                    |   `matA = A, roffA = i - 1, coffA = j - 1`
    !>  `lda`                           |   NONE (passed implicitly).
    !>  `b = B(i,j)`                    |   `matB = B, roffB = i - 1, coffB = j - 1`
    !>  `ldb`                           |   NONE (passed implicitly).
    !>  `c = C(i,j)`                    |   `matC = C, roffC = i - 1, coffC = j - 1`
    !>  `ldc`                           |   NONE (passed implicitly).
    !>  \endcond excluded
